data.title: Athletes Born on May 9
data.meta_description: Famous birthdays in sport for the 9th of May. Browse birthdays of sports stars, managers and coaches that were born on May 9.
data.text:
Adam Opel

German automobile manufacturer (founded Adam Opel AG), born in Rüsselsheim, Hesse, Prussia

Harry Vardon

Jersey golfer (6 time British Open champion, US Open 1900), born in Grouville, Jersey

George Duckworth, English cricket wicket-keeper (24 Tests, 60 dismissals), born in Warrington, Lancashire, England (d. 1966)

Lilí Álvarez, Spanish tennis player (Wimbledon 1926-28 runner-up), born in Rome, Italy (d. 1998)

Fred Warngård, Swedish athlete (d. 1950)

Betty Jameson, American golfer (US Open 1947, Western Open 1942, 54), born in Norman, Oklahoma (d. 2009)

Juan José Pizzuti, Argentine soccer striker and manager (12 caps; Racing Club de Avellaneda), born in Buenos Aires, Argentina (d. 2020)

1927 Ray Katt, American MLB baseball catcher, 1952-59 (World Series Champion - New York Giants, St. Louis Cardinals), and collegiate coach, 1971-93, born in New Braunfels, Texas (d. 1999)

Barbara Ann Scott, Canadian figure skater (Olympic gold 1948, World champion 1947-48), born in Ottawa, Ontario (d. 2012)

1928 Pancho González, American tennis player (US National C'ships singles 1948-49; Wimbledon & French Open Doubles, 1949; 13 x Pro Grand Slam titles), born in Los Angeles, California (d. 1995)

Conrad Hunte, Barbadian cricketer (great West Indian opener 1958-66), born in St. Andrew, Barbados (d. 1999)

Terry Downes, British middleweight boxing champion (1961-62), born in London (d. 2017)

Walt Corey, American football linebacker (AFL C'ship 1962, 66; AFL All-Star 1963; Dallas Texans/KC Chiefs) and coach (KC Chiefs, Buffalo Bills), born in Latrobe, Pennsylvania (d. 2022)

Ion Ţiriac, Romanian tennis manager

Ralph Boston

American athlete (Olympic gold long jump 1960, silver 1964, bronze 1968; first to break 27 feet [8.2m] barrier), born in Laurel, Mississippi

Dorothy Hyman, English athlete (Olympic silver 100m, bronze 200m 1960; bronze 4×100m relay 1964), born in Cudworth, England

1941 Howard Komives, American NBA star (NY Knicks, Buffalo Braves), born in Toledo, Ohio (d. 2009)

George Wilson. American basketball center (NCAA C'ship 1962 Uni of Cincinnati; Olympic gold 1964; Cincinnati Royals, Chicago Bulls, Seattle SuperSonics, Phoenix Suns), born in Meridian, Mississippi (d. 2023)

Maurice Foster, West Indian cricket batsman (14 Tests, 1 x 100, HS 125; Jamaica), born in St. Mary, Jamaica

Calvin Murphy, American basketball player

1948 John Mahaffey, American golfer (PGA Championship 1978; 10 PGA Tour titles), born in Kerrville, Texas

Ron Jackson, baseball player

Balazs Taroczy, Hungarian tennis star

Myra Blackwelder, American golfer (LPGA Rookie of the Year 1980), born in Lexington, Kemtucky

John Stuper, baseball pitcher (St Louis Cardinals)

Esko Rechardt, Finnish yachtsman (Olympic gold 1980)

Andrew Jones, New Zealand cricket batsman (39 Tests @ 44.27, 87 ODIs), born in Wellington, New Zealand

1959 Asantha De Mel, cricketer (pioneering Sri Lankan Test opening bowler)

Iain Butchart, cricket all-rounder (Zimbabwe, Test v Pak 1995)

Tony Gwynn

American Baseball HOF outfielder (15 x MLB All Star; 8 x NL batting champion; 5 × Gold Glove Award; SD Padres), born in Los Angeles, California

Miloslav Mečíř

Czech tennis player (Olympic gold 1988), born in Bojnice, Czechoslovakia

Marc Logan, NFL running back (Washington Redskins), born in Lexington, Kentucky

Steve Yzerman

Canadian Hockey Hall of Fame forward (Olympic gold 2002, Detroit Red Wings), born in Cranbrook, British Columbia

Mark Tinordi, Canadian NHL defenseman (Washington Capitals), born in Red Deer, Alberta

Bruce Pickens, NFL cornerback (Oakland Raiders)

1968 David Benoit, NBA forward (Utah Jazz, NJ Nets)

1968 Marie-José Pérec, French track and field athlete (Olympic gold 200m, 400m 1996), born in Basse-Terre, Guadeloupe

1968 Vince Workman, NFL running back (Packers, Panthers, Colts)

Carla Overbeck, American soccer defender (170 caps; Olympic gold 1996, silver 2000; FIFA Women's World Cup gold 1991, 99), born in Pasadena, California

1969 Renn Crichlow, canoeist (Olympics-8-92, 96), born in Ottawa, Ontario

Doug Christie, NBA guard/forward (Toronto Raptors)

Dan Hollander, figure skater (1996 Great Lakes champ), born in Royal Oak, Michigan

1972 Daniela Silivaș, Romanian gymnast (3 Olympic gold 1988), born in Deva, Romania

1972 Simon Hollingsworth, Australian 400m hurdler (Olympics 1992, 96)

Stephane Yelle, NHL center (Colorado Avalanche), born in Ottawa, Ontario

Brian Deegan, American freestyle motocross cyclist, born in Omaha, Nebraska

Iñigo Landaluze, Spanish cyclist

1977 Maggie Dixon, American college basketball coach (d. 2006)

Aaron Harang, American baseball player

1978 Leandro Damián Cufré, Argentine footballer

Brandon Webb, American baseball pitcher (MLB All-Star 2006, 07, 08; NL Cy Young Award 2006; NL wins leader 2006, 08; Arizona Diamondbacks), born in Ashland, Kentucky

Grant Hackett, Australian swimmer (Olympicss - gold, 2000 & 2004), born in Southport, Queensland

1980 Tony Schmidt, German racing driver

Bill Murphy, American baseball player

Tyler Lumsden, American baseball player

Prince Fielder, American baseball first baseman (6 x MLB All Star, NL HR leader 2007, MLB RBI leader 2009, Milwaukee Brewers), born in Ontario, California

Gints Freimanis, Latvian soccer right-back (13 caps; Jelgava 110 games), born in Saldus, Latvia (d. 2023)

1985 Jake Long, American football player

John Ryan Fitzpatrick, Canadian race truck driver

Jenni Hermoso, Spanish football player for Tigres UANL and Spain, born in Madrid, Spain

Majlinda Kelmendi, Kosovar-Albanian judoka (Olympic gold 2016), born in Peć, SFR Yugoslavia

Beth Mead, English footballer (Arsenal), born in Whitby, England
